name: General

widgets.name: Number of events by hostname
widgets.info: Devices typically generate more events when changes are made. If a large number of messages is seen on one or more devices then this may indicate a configuration change or possible a problem with the devices.

widgets.name: Number of events over time
widgets.info:
The number events should be consistent over time. There are several reasons why the number of events would not be consistent over time:

• Increase in the number of events

- The number of devices sending events has increased. In this scenario then a one-time increase in events would be expected.
- The number of events generated by a device typically increases when there is a problem happening. Check the error and warning widgets for more information.

• Decrease in the number of events

- The number of devices sending events has decreased. If the decrease in the number of devices sending events was intentional then a one-time decrease in events would be expected. If the decrease in the number of devices sending events was unintentional then this would indicate a potential problem in the environment. Check the unique count widget and vSphere integration for more information.

widgets.name: Unique event types
widgets.info:
Note: For performance reasons, it is recommended to run this query over a time range of 1 hour or less.

The number of event types should remain fairly consistent over time unless devices are added/removed from VCF Operations for Logs or new events are ingested. New event types may indicate changes to the environment or environmental issues.

Event types are unique message patterns that have been detected. While devices often generate a large number of events, many events are very similar except for some dynamic variables like timestamp, hostname, etc.

widgets.name: Number of error events by hostname
widgets.info: When issues are experienced on a device, the number of error events typically increases. If a large number of error messages is seen on one or more devices then this may indicate a problem with the devices.

widgets.name: Number of error events over time
widgets.info: When issues are experienced on a device, the number of error events typically increases. If a spike of error messages is seen this may indicate a problem within the environment.

widgets.name: Number of exception events by hostname
widgets.info: When issues are experienced on a device, the number of exception events typically increases. If a large number of exception messages is seen on one or more devices then this may indicate a problem with the devices.

widgets.name: Number of exception events over time
widgets.info: Exceptions are typically critical issues that only occur when there is a problem in an environment. If a spike of exception messages is seen this may indicate a problem within the environment. Note that this query will not match exception events prefixed with a keyword (e.g. XyzException).

author: Broadcom, Inc.
info:
The VMware Cloud Foundation Operations for Logs General Content Pack includes the following dashboards:
  • Overview - Provides generic information about any events being sent to your VCF Operations for Logs instance including errors, warnings, and exceptions.
  • Problems - Provides generic problem information discovered by VCF Operations for Logs' machine learning including event types and event trends.
  • Event Types - Provides information discovered by VCF Operations for Logs' machine learning including unique errors, warnings, and exceptions.
  • VCF Operations for Logs Agents - Provides information about configured VCF Operations for Logs Agents including configured filelog and winlog collection. For information about currently configured agents, visit the Agents page.
  • Syslog Agents - Provides information about configured syslog agents.
IMPORTANT: This content pack requires VCF Operations for Logs (previously vRLI) 4.0 or newer.
instructions: This is a preinstalled content pack. No need of any additional configuration.
upgradeInstructions: Thanks for upgrading! You are all set -- happy logging!
